classification.tableDescription: 2000-2004 Preneed Mortality Table – Male. Select and Ultimate
classification.comments: Study Data: Preneed life insurance is a specialized form of life insurance or annuity used to fund the predetermined expenses of a funeral, cremation or burial. Policies are issued on a limited underwriting or guaranteed issue basis and often exhibit mortality with a reverse select and ultimate pattern. Mortality experience data from ten companies which are active in the preneed market was collected by the Society of Actuaries (SOA) for the years 2000-2004. Polices converting to Extended Term Insurance (ETI) or Reduced Paid-up (RPU) were included if the policy changed status prior to 1/1/2000. Deaths associated with converted policies were however omitted. The study was based on a total adjusted exposure of 1,708,924 and total adjusted deaths of 143,422. Methodology: The attained age and duration for each policy holder was calculated using issue age and year of exposure. The exposures and deaths by company and policy year were then combined to create the raw experience mortality table. In aggregating the data, some contributors’ exposure and deaths were scaled back by a factor so that the analysis was more representative of all the submitting companies. From the data, the effect of selection appeared to wear off after 5 years. A moving average method was used to initially smooth the raw data for issue ages 50 and greater. Interpolation and trend techniques were used for younger and older ages where the experience data was sparse. The resultant table was graduated to create the final mortality table. Several iterative processes of refining and smoothing the graduated table to mimic the true pattern of mortality experience were performed. Data Transcription Errors: None. Data Certified: 02/2013
